	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tokumaru</b> [ Sun Jan 27, 2013 11:25 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: How to Update a Palette mid game?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">mysteriousity wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I know that one write to $2005 turns off Vertical Scrolling.</div><br />Scrolling is not something that the NES does by itself, so you can't turn it on or off. What happens is that you just set the scroll to known values, causing rendering to start at the specified pixel coordinates. If you change those coordinates over time, you get scrolling. Writing $00 to $2005 sets the horizontal scroll to $00 (i.e. rendering will start from pixel 0 - the absolute left - of the name table), the second write affects the vertical scroll (0 is the absolute top of the name table).<br /><br />Using $2006/$2007 messes up the internal address register the PPU uses to render the screen, so you must always set the scroll properly (write once to $2000 to select a name table and twice to $2005 so set the horizontal scroll and the vertical scroll) after using $2006/$2007 for updating VRAM.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

